solutions.content:
We are trying to find a number that doesn't trust anyone -> doesn't appear in the left side of a connection, and everyone trusts it -> has all other numbers in it's left side.
So we use a helping vector `trust_judge`.
For each time we see a number in the left side, we decrement one, and in the right side - we increment one.
Now, at the end, if the number is a judge, we should have exactly `n-1`, because we saw it n-1 times in the right side and none in the left side.

**Time Complexity:** O(n)
**Space Complexity:** O(n)
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findJudge(int n, vector<vector<int>>& trust) {
        vector<int> trust_judge(n+1, 0);

        for (auto t : trust) {
            trust_judge[t[0]]--;
            trust_judge[t[1]]++;
        }

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++)
            if (trust_judge[i] == n-1) return i;

        return -1;
    }
};
```
