solutions.content:
* The 2 conditions here are : 
      1. Everyone trusts the town judge
      2. The town judge trusts no one

**APPROACH :**

* We can solve this problem using indegree & outdegree of a node in a graph.
* If person ```a``` trusts person ```b```, there's an outgoing edge ```from a to b```. and an incoming edge ```to b from a```.
* So the **town judge** has ```n-1``` incoming edges & ```0``` outgoing edges.

**ALGORITHM :** 

* Create an array ```inout``` in which ```inout[i]``` stores the sum of indegree & outdegree of person ```i```(outdegree is -ve & indegree is +ve).
* We traverse the ```trust``` array, & for every element ```t``` in ```trust``` we do ```t[0]--``` (outdegree - ```t[0]``` trusts ```t[1]```) & ```t[1]++``` (indegree - ```t[1]``` has gained trust of ```t[0]```).
* Finally, we traverse the count array & for any i if ```count[i] == n-1```, then that person trusts no one & everone(all ```n-1``` persons) trusts that person. So we return ```i```.

Time Complexity : O(N); N= ```trust.size()```

Auxiliary Space : O(n); n = no. of people (The first line in the input)

**Code :**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findJudge(int n, vector<vector<int>>& trust) {
        vector<int> inout(n+1, 0);

        for(auto t : trust){
            inout[t[0]]--; //outdegree of a node
            inout[t[1]]++; //indegree of a node
        }
        for(int i=1; i<n+1; i++){   //there are n people labelled from 1 to n
            if(inout[i]==n-1) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

