Indegree and Outdegree based approach.
Indegree of a node is the number of edges coming 'in' to that node.Similary outdegree is defined as the number of nodes going 'out' of that node.
Please note that Indegree and Outdegree is defined for Directed Graphs.
The two conditions in the description in terms of Indegree and Outdegree are as follows:
1) Outdegree of the Judge node will be 0.
2) InDegree of the Judge node will be n-1.

**Here is the code:**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findJudge(int n, vector<vector<int>>& trust) {
        int outDeg[n+1],inDeg[n+1];
        memset(outDeg,0,sizeof(outDeg));
        memset(inDeg,0,sizeof(inDeg));
        int m=trust.size();
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            outDeg[trust[i][0]]++;
            inDeg[trust[i][1]]++;
        }
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++)if(outDeg[i]==0&&inDeg[i]==n-1)return i;
        return -1;
    }
};
```
