# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
### 1. HashSet + Array Approach
1. Keep an `freq` integer array to count the number of people that trusts a particular person.
2. Have a HashSet `trustSet` which will hold the all the people who trust someone or the other.
3. Now iterate from `1` to `n` and check `if(freq[i] == n-1 && !trustSet.contains(i))` i.e. the `i`th person is trusted by all and the `i`th person trusts no one.
4. Edge case: If `n == 1`, that would mean `trust = [[]]`, hence return 1


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findJudge(int n, int[][] trust) {
        if(n == 1) return 1;

        int[] freq = new int[n+1];
        Set<Integer> trustSet = new HashSet<>();

        for(int i=0; i<trust.length; i++){
            trustSet.add(trust[i][0]);
            freq[trust[i][1]] += 1;
        }
        for(int i=1; i<=n; i++){
            if(freq[i] == n-1 && !trustSet.contains(i)) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

### 2. Single Array Approach
1. In this appraoch we just keep a single integer array `freq`. 
2. If we have `trust[i] = [a,b]` we simple increment `freq[b]` by 1 and decrement `freq[a]` by 1.
3. This would make sure that if `i`th person is trusted by all and also if that person trusts no one then `freq[i] == n-1`.
4. So Just iterate over the array and check if frequency of any element is `n-1`.
5. Edge case: If `n == 1`, that would mean `trust = [[]]`, hence return 1

# Code
